  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most married Brisbane sellers assume that because they are married, both partners automatically have a legal say in whether the family home can be sold. That assumption is wrong, or at least incomplete. In Queensland, the certificate of title is the legal record that determines who has the power to sell. If only one spouse is named on the title, that spouse can in principle enter into a contract of sale without the other's signature, even if the property is the family home and both partners have lived in it for years.</p>

      <p>That legal starting point is often a surprise. It matters because it shapes how married couples should approach a sale, especially in separation scenarios, blended family situations, or pre-marriage property that is being sold after the wedding. The good news is that Queensland law and federal family law provide meaningful protections for the non-title spouse. But those protections require action, not assumption. This article sets out how title works, what the non-title spouse's options actually are, and the practical framework most couples use to get through a sale without turning it into a dispute.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The starting position: only the registered owner can sell</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, land ownership is a function of the Torrens title system. The certificate of title held by the Queensland Titles Registry records who legally owns the property and in what shares. When a property is registered, ownership takes one of three forms: sole ownership by one person, joint tenancy by two or more people where each has an undivided whole interest with right of survivorship, or tenancy in common where two or more people each hold a defined share.</p>

      <p>Under all three forms, the legal power to sell sits with the registered owner or owners. A sole owner can sign a contract on their own. Joint tenants and tenants in common must all sign, because each is a registered owner. No other person, married to the owner or not, has a legal right to sign the contract of sale, veto a listing, or block a settlement simply on the basis of the relationship.</p>

      <p>This is a distinct legal question from who benefits from the sale proceeds. Under family law, the non-title spouse may have a substantial claim on the property or on its proceeds even without being on the title. But that is a separate system of rights, enforced through different processes. The Queensland title system is narrow and formal: it tells you who can sign, and nothing more.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What this means for married couples in practice</h2>
      <p>If both spouses are registered on the title, whether as joint tenants or tenants in common, both must sign the contract of sale, the transfer document, and the settlement paperwork. Neither can act alone. This is the most common structure for owner-occupied homes in Brisbane and creates no difficulty when both spouses agree on the sale.</p>

      <p>If only one spouse is on the title, that spouse can, in principle, list the property, accept an offer, and sign a contract without the other spouse's consent. Whether that is wise is a different question. In most family law scenarios, proceeding to sale without consulting the non-title spouse is a fast route to litigation and exposes the sale itself to potential disruption. But the starting legal position is that the title-holder has the signing power.</p>

      <p>There are common reasons a title may be held in only one spouse's name. The property may have been purchased before the marriage. It may have been transferred into one name for asset protection or tax reasons, particularly where one partner runs a business with personal liability exposure. It may reflect a deliberate estate planning decision. Or the title may never have been updated following a change in circumstances that should have prompted a transfer. The reason the title is structured the way it is often has nothing to do with any intention to exclude the other spouse from the property's value.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The protections available to the non-title spouse</h2>
      <p>A non-title spouse who is concerned that a sale may proceed without their consent has three meaningful legal tools available. Each works differently and each requires timely action.</p>

      <p>The first is a caveat lodged on the Queensland Titles Registry. A caveat is a formal notice claiming a legal or equitable interest in the property. Once lodged, it prevents any transfer of the title until the caveat is withdrawn, lapses, or is removed by court order. A non-title spouse may lodge a caveat if they have a genuine claim of interest, for example as a contributor to the purchase price, as a contributor to mortgage repayments or substantial improvements, or on the basis of a constructive or resulting trust. Caveats are serious legal documents. Lodging one without a reasonable basis can expose the caveator to damages. Advice from a solicitor is essential before lodging.</p>

      <p>The second is an order under the Family Law Act 1975. The Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia has jurisdiction to make orders affecting property where a relationship has broken down or is at risk of breakdown. These orders can include injunctions preventing sale, orders for sale on specific terms, or orders dividing the proceeds of any sale. The court can also make orders before a relationship has formally ended if there is a genuine risk that one party will deal with property in a way that defeats the other party's eventual entitlements.</p>

      <p>The third is a claim of equitable interest. Where the non-title spouse has contributed financially to the purchase, to the mortgage, or to significant improvements, Australian equitable doctrines may recognise a constructive trust or resulting trust in their favour. The practical effect is that a court can declare the non-title spouse to be the beneficial owner of a share of the property regardless of what the title says. Proving a trust claim requires careful evidence of contributions and intentions, and the argument usually supports either a caveat or a family law application rather than standing alone.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When these issues typically arise</h2>
      <p>Most marriages never encounter the question of unilateral sale authority. Both spouses agree the property should be sold, both attend the appraisal, both sign the listing authority even if only one name appears on the contract of sale, and the transaction proceeds as planned. The question only becomes real in a handful of scenarios.</p>

      <p>Separation and relationship breakdown is the most common. One spouse wants to sell to realise proceeds or to move on, the other wants to retain the home for the children or believes the timing is wrong. If the title is held by the spouse wishing to sell, the other spouse needs to act promptly to protect their position.</p>

      <p>Pre-marriage property being sold after the marriage is another. A home purchased before the wedding in one name is usually sold in that same name, but the marriage, the length of cohabitation, and any contributions the other spouse has made to the mortgage or improvements create potential interests that should be considered before listing.</p>

      <p>Blended family and estate planning scenarios are a third. Where a surviving spouse has remarried and the home is held in one name, children from a previous relationship may have their own interests to consider. The sale of the family home before death can crystallise or disrupt plans that had been made on the assumption the home would pass through an estate.</p>

      <p>Tax and liability-driven structures are the fourth. A home may be in one spouse's name because the other runs a business with personal liability. A sale in that structure is legally straightforward for the title-holder but raises questions for the couple about what happens to the proceeds and how they are preserved.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the title-holder should think about</h2>
      <p>If you are the spouse whose name is on the title and you are considering selling, the legal position gives you the authority to act. The practical position is almost always that acting without consulting your spouse is a mistake.</p>

      <p>In a healthy marriage where the sale reflects a shared decision, your spouse's consent is a given and the question is only about process. In a strained marriage or one nearing separation, a unilateral listing signals a dispute and invites the non-title spouse to take every legal protection available. A caveat lodged during your campaign will almost certainly delay or collapse your sale. A family law injunction applied for after contracts are exchanged can disrupt settlement and expose you to damages for breach.</p>

      <p>Even where the sale ultimately proceeds, the financial and emotional cost of a sale conducted in the teeth of a dispute routinely exceeds the value gained from acting unilaterally. Engaging openly with your spouse from the outset, and offering to involve independent legal advice for both of you, is almost always the better strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the non-title spouse should do if concerned</h2>
      <p>If you are the non-title spouse and you are concerned that a sale may proceed without your consent, act promptly and methodically. Waiting until the property has been listed, or until a contract has been signed, significantly narrows your options.</p>

      <p>Obtain independent legal advice from a family law solicitor as soon as possible. The advice should cover your position under family law, whether a caveat is appropriate, and whether interim court orders are a realistic option. Australian family law solicitors are experienced in these scenarios and can usually give you a clear read on your exposure within one meeting.</p>

      <p>Document your financial contributions to the property. Deposit contributions, mortgage repayments from your income, payments for significant improvements, and contributions to rates, insurance, and maintenance are all potentially relevant. Bank statements, loan statements, and records of major works are the evidence base for both a caveat claim and a family law application.</p>

      <p>Consider whether lodging a caveat is appropriate. A caveat is a powerful tool but carries risk if lodged without a reasonable basis. A solicitor will advise whether your circumstances justify one. In many cases, the fact that a caveat could be lodged is sufficient leverage to bring the title-holding spouse to the negotiating table without actually needing to lodge.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework most couples use</h2>
      <p>The vast majority of married Brisbane sellers where one spouse is not on the title proceed harmoniously, because both partners agree the sale makes sense and are aligned on timing and price. In that scenario, the title structure is a paperwork detail rather than a legal issue. The contract is signed by the title-holder, the proceeds are distributed as the couple agrees, and the sale proceeds as if both were on the title.</p>

      <p>Where the couple is not aligned, the sale should not proceed until the disagreement is resolved. Forcing a sale through while the other spouse opposes it, even where legally permitted, produces worse outcomes for both parties than working through the disagreement in advance. Where separation is already on the table, the right sequence is to complete the family law property settlement first, or at least agree the property-related terms of that settlement, before listing. A sale that occurs in the middle of an unresolved family law matter will be litigated over, and the agents, solicitors, and court system will consume a significant share of the proceeds that could have gone to the family.</p>

      <p>For a clean sale, both spouses should be involved in the campaign decisions regardless of whose name is on the title. Both should attend the appraisal, both should review the marketing plan, and both should consent to the price strategy in writing. A cooperative approach from day one avoids every issue this article discusses.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A final note on legal advice</h2>
      <p>This article describes the general structure of how title, consent, caveats, and family law orders interact in Queensland. It is not legal advice and cannot substitute for advice on your specific circumstances. Property ownership structures, relationship law, and the interaction between state title law and federal family law are areas where small variations in the facts produce large differences in legal outcome. If there is any meaningful question about whether a sale should proceed in your situation, engage a Queensland property solicitor and a family law solicitor before listing.</p>

